Stereoselective  hydrolytic  opening  of  epoxide  rings  are  attractive  in  asymmetric  synthesis,  since

the  resultant  vicinal  diols  are  valuable  building  blocks  of  chiral  drugs  and  bioactive  compounds  (1,2).  In  biological  systems,  epoxide  hydrolases  (EHs)  are  extensively  studied  to  catalyze  the  cofactor-independent  hydrolysis  of  epoxides  to  vicinal diols (3,4). The enzymatic mechanisms of  EHs  have  been  well  characterized,  by  substrate  selectivity,  crystal  structures,  combined  with  molecular  dynamics  simulations,  and  directed  evolution  approaches  (5-9).  Most  EHs  belong  to  members  of  a  family  with  an  α/β  hydrolase-fold,  sharing an catalytic core domain and a cap domain  (10). The α/β-EHs usually feature a catalytic triad  and an oxirane oxygen hole that enable a two-step  mechanism  involving  an  SN2  reaction  and  ester  hydrolysis (Figure 1A) (10,11). The catalytic triad  contains  two  aspartates  (Asp)  and  one  histidine  (His)  (10).  In  the  first  step,  the  attack  of  the  nucleophilic  aspartate  ion  (Asp)  to  the  epoxide  linked  ring  enzyme-acyloxy-substrate  adduct  (5,6).  In  the  second step, the His and the other Asp activate a  the  to  water  enzyme-acyloxy-substrate  and  release the products as trans-vicinal diols (12,13).  The  oxirane  oxygen  hole  contains  a  pair  of  tyrosines  (Tyr),  which  are  proposed  to  donate  hydrogen  bonds  to  the  oxirane  oxygen,  thereby  assisting  the  first  step  of  reaction  sequence  by  activating  the  epoxide  and  stabilizing  the  formed  oxyanion  family  of  EHs,  represented  limonene-

the  oxirane  oxygen,  thereby  assisting  the  first  step  of  reaction  sequence  by  activating  the  epoxide  and  stabilizing  the  formed  oxyanion  family  of  EHs,  represented  limonene-1,2-epoxide  hydrolases,  catalyzes  a  one-step  mechanism  with  SN2  ring-opening  of  the  epoxide  ring  by  an  enzyme-activated water molecule (Fig. 1B) (15).    These  EH-catalyzed  epoxide  ring-openings  follow  SN2-type  with  mechanism  generally  backside  attack  by  the  nucleophile  resulting  in  inversion  of  stereoconfiguration  at  the  reactive  carbon  center  (6,15).  However,  engineering  control  of  the  regioselectivity  into  the  epoxide

ring opening reaction remains challenging for EHs  (15,16).  In  synthetic  epoxide  hydrolysis,  the  regioselectivity depends on the substituents on the  epoxide  carbons  (17)  and  the  strength  of  the  nucleophilic  the  EHs-catalyzed epoxide ring-opening reactions, the  regioselectivity is influenced more by the structure  of  the  enzyme  active  site  (18).  These  steric  constraints  can  potentially  also  control  the  stereochemistry  of  the  product. This  hypothesis is  supported  by  enzyme  engineering  of  EHs  by  directed  evolution  strategy  or  small  mutagenic  library  screening  (15,16,19-21).  Unfortunately,  mechanistic details of what causes regioselectivity  improvement of engineered EHs are still elusive.

In the biosynthesis of vicinal diols, the chirality  of  these  functional  natural  products  derived  from  oxiranes, plays important roles toward directing of  post-modifications of the hydroxy groups,  such as  glycosylation.  Representative  acylation  examples  include  the  EH  Nasvi-EH1  involved  in  the biosynthesis of an insect sex attractant (22), the  α/β-EHs  NcsF2  and  SgcF-catalyzed  epoxide-ring  opening in the biosynthesis of enediyne antitumor  antibiotics  neocarzinostatins  and  C-1027  (23,24),  the  TsrI-mediated  endopeptidyl  hydrolysis  and  in  epoxide  the  thiostrepton  Alp1U-catalyzed  of  epoxide  epoxykinamycins  (Fig.  1C)  (26).  Interestingly,  we  have shown that the Alp1U found in Streptomyces  ambofaciens also uses fluostatin (FST) C (1) from  Micromonospora rosaria (27,28) as a substrate and  catalyzes the epoxide hydrolysis to produce a pair  of  stereoisomers  FST  C1  (1a)  and  FST  C2  (1b).  The  origins  of  these  stereoisomers  were  proposed  to  result  from  non-regioselective  hydrolysis  by  nucleophilic attack at the C-2 and C-3 position of 1  (Fig. 1C) (29).  absolute  determined  stereochemistry of the two products FSTs C1 (1a)  opening/macrocyclization  and  hydrolysis

and  C2  (1b)  from  Alp1U-catalyzed  epoxide  ring-opening  of  FST  C  (1),  and  solved  the X-ray  crystal  structure  of  Alp1U. We have previously shown that Alp1U converts  fluostatin  C  (1)  to  two  stereoisomers  1a  and  1b,  the  structures  of  which  have  not  been  elucidated  yet  (29).  Subsequently,  compounds  1a  and  1b  large-scale  enzymatic  were  reaction  of  with  Alp1U  and  1  to  elucidate  the  structure. Both 1a and 1b had a molecular formula  of  C18H14O7  (m/z  341.0672  [M  -  H]-  for  1a,  m/z  341.0673 [M - H]- for 1b, calcd for 341.0667, Fig.  S1). The NMR data for 1a and 1b (Fig. 2, Figs. S1  and  S2)  showed  high  similarity  to  those  of  the  previously  characterized  FST  C  (1)  (28).  The  relatively  more  downfield  shifts  of  the  C-2  and  C-3  (Table  S1)  in  1a  and  1b,  compared  to  the  same  carbons  of  1,  suggested  the  presence  of  a  vicinal diol subunit at C-2/C-3 in both compounds,  instead of the epoxide moiety at C-2/C-3 in 1 (28).  The  trans  relative  configuration  of  H-1  and  CH3-3  in  1a  was  indicated  by  the  NOESY  correlation of OH-1 and H3-12 (Fig. 2A). In order  to determine the relative configuration of H-1 and  H-2, a propylidene acetal derivative of 1a (1a-At)  relative  was  prepared

The  in  1a-At  NOESY  correlation  of  H-2/OH-3  confirmed the relative trans configuration of OH-2  and  OH-3  (Fig.  2A,  Fig.  S3).  Therefore,  the  relative  configuration  of  the  1,2,3-triol  moiety  in  1a was determined as (1R*,2R*,3S*) in accordance  with the configurations of 1a-At. Considering that  1a was a ring-opened product of  2,3-epoxide  1, it  thus  must  preserve  the  original  (R)  absolute  configuration at C-1, the absolute configuration of  1a was assigned as (1R, 2R,3S). The trans relative  configuration of H-1 and H-2 in 1b was indicated  by  the  NOESY  correlation  of  H-1  and  OH-2  and  the large value of the  3JH-1, H-2 coupling constant in  methanol-d4  (Table  S3,  Fig.  S4). To  learn  more  details  about  the  catalytic  mechanism of the Alp1U reaction, the ligand-free  structure  of  N-terminal  His6-tagged  Alp1U  was  determined  to  2.45  Å,  with  four  chains  per  asymmetric  unit  (Table  1,  Fig.  S6).  The  four  Alp1U chains form two dimers according to PISA  calculation  (33).  Each  chain  takes  the  canonical  α/β-hydrolase  fold,  comprising  an  catalytic  domain  (residues  27–166  and  251–319) linked  to  an α-helical cap (residues 167–250) (Fig. 3A). The  26  residues  at  the  N-terminus  that  share  no  sequence  similarity  to  reported  crystal  structures  of  EHs  are  not  resolved  in  the  structure,  likely  caused  by  the  flexibility  of  this  region.  A  PDB  database search of the Alp1U coordinates by Dali  server (34) reveals that Alp1U is most similar to a  fluoroacetate  dehalogenase  (FAcD,  PDB  ID:  3R3U, Z-score 38.5) (35). However, Alp1U shares  a conserved overall fold (Z-score 38.2–25) with a  batch  of  α/β-EHs,  despite  low  identities  in  their  amino  acid  sequences  (<30%),  including  the  studied  epichlorohydrin  epoxide  extensively  Agrobacterium  (EchA)  hydrolase  radiobacter AD1 (PDB ID: 1EHY) (6), the BmEH  from  Bacillus  megaterium  ECU1001  (PDB  ID:  4IO0) (13), the  human soluble epoxide hydrolase  (sEH,  PDB  ID:  4HAI)  (36),  and  the  bacterial  vir

Bacillus  megaterium  ECU1001  (PDB  ID:  4IO0) (13), the  human soluble epoxide hydrolase  (sEH,  PDB  ID:  4HAI)  (36),  and  the  bacterial  virulence  factor  EH  (cif)  from  Pseudomonas  aeruginosa  (PDB  ID:  5TND)  (12)  (Fig.  S7).  Structural alignment of Alp1U with these α/β-EHs  reveals  that,  the  catalytic  triad  of  classic  EHs  is  conserved in Alp1U, consisting of residues D137,  H300 and D161 (Fig. 3B). We propose that Alp1U  ring-opening  two-step  epoxide  catalyzes  a

reaction  as  the  classic  α/β-EHs  (Fig.  1A).  In  the  first  step,  D137  launches  a  nucleophilic  attack  at  the  epoxide  carbon  and  forms  a  covalent  alkyl-enzyme  intermediate.  In  the  second  step,  H300  activates  a  water  molecule,  in  cooperation  with  D161,  hydrolyzing  alkyl-enzyme  intermediate to release the vicinal diol product and  D137.  However, the Alp1U active site is different from  those of classic α/β-EHs in the key oxirane oxygen  hole (Fig. 3B). The canonical oxirane oxygen hole  of  α/β-EHs  contains  two  Tyr  residues  that  play  critical roles in the first catalytic step, by forming  H-bonds  with  the  epoxide  oxygen  and  stabilizing  the  liberated  oxirane  oxyanion  (Fig.  1A  and  3B)  (8,14)  However,  Alp1U  has  only  one  of  the  two  conserved  Tyrs  (Y247),  while  the  second  Tyr  is  putatively  replaced  by  a  tryptophan  (W186)  with  its indole side chain being positioned for donating  a  H-bond  to  the  oxirane  oxygen  (Fig.  3B).  Also,  the  indole  side  chain  of  the  adjacent  W187  is  properly  positioned  to  donate  an  H-bond  to  the  oxirane  oxygen  (Fig.  3B).  Therefore,  the  three  residues  W186,  W187  and  Y247  putatively  form  an atypical oxirane oxygen hole in Alp1U to donor  H-bonds to the epoxide oxygen.  Substrate regioselectivity by oxirane oxygen hole  engineering

To  confirm  the  proposed  roles  of  the  catalytic  residues,  the  Alp1U  mutants  were  generated  by  site-directed  mutagenesis  (Fig.  3C).  As  expected,  three  separate  mutants,  D137N,  H300F,  and  H300G  mutants  completely  abolished  catalytic  activity  for  1  (Fig.  3C).  The  W186F  mutant  completely  lost  the  activity,  while  the  W187F  mutant maintained the activity (Fig. 3C). It seems  that  W186,  required  catalytically  to  donate  H-bond  to  the  oxirane  oxygen in 1. Subsequently, the W186Y mutant was  made to mimic the classic oxirane oxygen hole in  EHs  (10).  However,  W186Y  showed  no  activity  (Fig.  3C),  likely  because  the  side  chain  of  Y186  could  not  properly  orient  to  interact  with  the  oxirane oxygen.

It should be noted that a histidine (H115) forms  the oxirane oxygen hole with Y219 in the bacterial  virulence  factor  EH  cif  (Fig.  3B)  (37),  a  W186H  mutant  was  also  constructed.  However,  the  W186H  mutant  only  showed  trace  catalytic  activity  for  the  epoxide  ring-opening  of  1  (Fig.  3C).  The  conserved  Y247  was  expected  to  assist  the epoxide ring-opening reaction by donating  an  H-bond  to  the  oxirane  oxygen.  Surprisingly,  the  retained  most  activity,  but  Y247F  mutant  selectively  produced  1b  (98%),  preferring  a  nucleophilic attack at C-3 (Figs. 3C and 3D). The  substrate  conversion  rates  of  W187F  and  Y247F  suggests  that  neither  W187  nor  the  conserved  Y247 in Alp1U is a key H-bond donor to stabilize  the oxirane oxygen of 1. To verify this hypothesis,  the W187F/Y247F double mutant was constructed.  Unexpectedly,  the  Alp1UW187F/Y247F  mutant  selectively  produced  1a  (94%)  as  a  result  of  preferentially attacking at C-2. These observations  are  in  sharp  contrast  to  previous  reports  that  classic α/β-EHs slightly lost the activity if one of  the  two  catalytic  Tyr  residues  in  the  oxirane  oxygen hole was mutated and became completely  inactive if both Tyr residues were mutated (7). To  the  best  of  our  knowledge,  such  significant  regioselectivity  improvement  and  switch  by  mutated  residues  of  the  oxirane  oxygen  hole  in  Alp1U  are  unprecedented  in  EHs  that  catalyze  epoxide ring-opening reactions.

Structural basis for the switch in regioselectivity  To investigate how the Alp1U mutants achieved  the  regioselectivity,  the  crystal  structures  of  the  Alp1UY247F (1.78 Å) and Alp1UW187F/Y247F (2.1 Å)  mutants  were  determined  in  complex  with  the  substrate FST C (1), by soaking with an excess of  1  (Table  1).  In  both  crystal  structures,  the  clear  electron density of 1 is observed (Fig. 4B and Fig.  S8).  Superposition  reveals  that  the  two  structure  the  complexes  are  essentially  apo-Alp1U structure (Fig. S9). The catalytic cavity  of  Alp1U  forms  a  deep  groove,  with  a  negatively  charged  surface,  which  binds  the  substrate  FST  C  (1) (Fig. 4A). FST C (1) is bound to Alp1U mainly  by  direct  and  water-mediated  hydrogen  bond  networks (Fig. 4B). The OH-1 hydroxyl group of 1  orients  to  the  inner  side  of  the  active  site.  Therefore, the O-acyl or O-methyl derivatization at  OH-1 could hamper FSTs to enter the Alp1U active  site, for steric crowding effect. This might explain  our  previously  reported  phenomenon  that  Alp1U  fail to convert FSTs containing O-acyl or O-methyl  group at C1 position (29).

Similar  binding  patterns  of  1  are  observed  in  both  structures  of  Alp1UY247F and  Alp1UW187F/Y247F  in complex with 1, and suggest that Alp1U uses the  same  epoxide  ring-opening  mechanism  as  that  of  classic  α/β-EHs  (Fig.  4C-4E).  In  both  structures  (Fig. 4C and 4D), the carboxyl side chain of D137  locates just below the epoxide ring of 1, ready for  the  nucleophilic  attack.  H300  locates  adjacent  to  D137  and  forms  hydrogen  bond  with  D161,  consistent  with  its  general  role  to  activate  one  the  covalent  water  molecule  for  hydrolyzing  substrate-enzyme  adduct  and  the  subsequent  release of D137. The epoxide ring of FST C (1) is  accommodated in the putative oxirane oxygen hole  defined  by  the  side  chains  of  W186,  W187  and  Y247  (Fig.  S10).  W186  is  perfectly  positioned  to  synchronously  protonate  the  epoxide  oxygen,  consistent with its critical role for the activity. The  epoxide  oxygen  of  1  locates  in  hydrogen  bond  distance (Fig. 4F) to the indole N-H of W187 (3.24  Å)  and  OH  of  Y247  (2.81  Å).  However,  the  N-H···O  angle  and  O-H···O  angle  (Fig.  4F)  are  inappropriate  to  donate  H-bonds,  considering  that  the  ideal  X-H···Y  angle  for  hydrogen  bond  is  generally  linear  or  close  to  180°  (38).  This  may  explain why the W187F and Y247F mutants retain  the catalytic activity.

Structural  alignments  of  Alp1U,  Alp1UY247F/1  and  Alp1UW187F/Y247F/1  complexes  reveal  highly  overlapped  D137,  H300,  D161  and  Y247,  but  a  slight  displacement  of  W186  and  the  adjacent  W187  (Fig.  4F).  Structural  comparison  reveals  that  the  substrate  1  in  Alp1UW187F/Y247F  adopts  a  in  ~20°  anticlockwise  comparison  with  that  in  Alp1UY247F.  We  propose  that  the  substrate  rotation  is  caused  by  repulsive  forces  from  the  two  hydrophobic  side  chains  of  F247  and  F187  in  Alp1UW187F/Y247F.  This  rotation  brings the carboxyl oxygen of D137 significantly  closer  to  C-2  of  1  in  the  Alp1UW187F/Y247F/1  complex  (2.91  Å)  than  in  the  Alp1UY247F/1  complex  (3.18  Å).  This  new  positioning  likely  directs  the  regioselective  attack  at  C-2  of  the  epoxide  ring  to  selectively  produce  1a  (94%).  This  observation  is  consistent  with  previous  studies  describing  the  distances  between  the  nucleophile  and  epoxide  carbons  as  essential  toward  determining  the  regioselectivity  of  other  EHs  (14,15,20).  However,  the  Y247F  mutant  prefers  a  regioselective  attack  at  C-3  of  1  to  produce  1b  (98%),  despite  the  similar  distances  between  the  nucleophile  D137  and  C-2  (3.18  Å)  and between D137 and the C-3 carbon (3.24 Å) in  the Al

to  produce  1b  (98%),  despite  the  similar  distances  between  the  nucleophile  D137  and  C-2  (3.18  Å)  and between D137 and the C-3 carbon (3.24 Å) in  the Alp1UY247F/1 complex. It is suggested from the  Alp1UY247F/1 complex that the hydrophobic effect  of the phenyl side chain, introduced by the Y247F  mutation, disfavors the carboxyl anion of D137 to  approach  C-2  of  1  and  largely  reduces  the  preference for attack at C-2. Thus, Alp1UY247F led  to  a  regioselective  attack  at  C-3.  The  C-3  selectivity  of  the  Y247F  mutant suggests that the  regioselectivity for epoxide hydrolysis may not be  the  solely  determined  by  interacting atoms, especially when the distances to  similar. The  single  site  mutant  Y247F  regioselectively attacks at C-3 (98%) of FST C (1)  to  form  1a,  the  (1R,2R,3S)-isomer,  while  the  double  mutant  W187F/Y247F  prefers  attacking  the  regioselectively  at  C-2  two  (1R,2S,3R)-1b.  Crystal  structures  of  mutants  with  distinctly  different  regioselectivities  in  complex  with  FST  C  (1)  were  determined  to  reveal slight conformation changes of the substrate  and  residues  of  the  oxirane  oxygen  hole.  These  structural and mutagenesis studies of Alp1U and its  mutants  provided  further  insight  into  the  factors  governing  the  regioselectivity  of  α/β-EHs,  which  suggests that other parameters such as hydrophobic  effects  should  be  considered,  in  addition  to  the  distance of the interacting atoms.

Experiment procedures  General  materials.  Chemicals,  and  molecular  biological  reagents  were  purchased  from  standard  commercial  sources  and  used  according  to  the  manufacturers’ recommendations. CD spectra were  recorded  on  a  Chirascan  circular  dichroism  1H  spectrometer  (Applied  Photophysics  Co.).  NMR,  13C  NMR,  and  2D  NMR  spectra  were  recorded on either Bruker Bruker 700 spectrometer  tetramethylsilane  (TMS)  as  the  internal  with  standard.  High-resolution  electrospray  ionization  mass  (HRESIMS)  data  were  measured  on  a  MaXis  4G  UHR-TOFMS  Inc.).  DNA  (Bruker  Daltonics  spectrometer  primers  used  in  listed  Supplementary Table 5.  Cloning,  expression  and  puriﬁcation  of  Alp1U  and  variants.  The  cloning  and  overexpression  of  Alp1U  was  performed  basically  as  previously  reported (29). Briefly, the Alp1U coding sequence  was  ampliﬁed  and  subcloned  into  pET28a(+)  vector  with  N-terminal  6-His  tag.  Site-directed  mutagenesis  of  Alp1U  was  carried  out according to  manufacturer's instructions (Fast  Mutagenesis  The  W187F/Y247F double mutant is constructed using  the verified Y247F plasmid as template.

Alp1U  and  mutants  were  expressed  in  E.  coli  BL21(DE3) cells. For fermentation, a 1-L culture  using Lysogeny Broth medium supplemented with  0.1 mM kanamycin was grown at 37 °C until the  OD600  reached  0.5−0.7  and  then  was  induced  IPTG  with  (isopropyl-β-D-1-thiogalactopyranoside)  and  allowed  to  grow  at  16  °C  overnight.  For  purification, cells collected by centrifugation were  resuspended in lysis buffer (50 mM Tris-HCl, 500  mM  NaCl,  10%  glycerol,  pH8.0),  lysed  by  three  through  a  ultrahigh-pressure  JN-mini  passes  homogenizer  machine  Juneng  Nono$Bio  Technology  Co.  Ltd,  Guangzhou,  China), and then centrifuged for 45 min at 11000  rpm at 4 °C. His6-tagged proteins were purified by  Ni2+-NTA  agarose  (GE  Healthcare,  17–5318–03)  affinity  chromatography.  For  crystallization,  the  further  purification  using  target  protein  superdex  200  (buffer containing  20  mM Tris, pH  7.5, 200 mM NaCl, 1 mM DTT), and concentrated  to  ~20  mg  mL−1  using  a  Ultracel  30K  filter  (Millipore).  The  purity  of  wild-type  Alp1U  and  variants were analyzed by SDS-PAGE (Fig. S11),  and  the  final  concentration  was  determined  by  NanoDrop 8000 (Thermo Scientific, USA).

In vitro Enzyme assays. In vitro enzyme assays of  recombinant  Alp  1U  and  mutant  variants  were  conducted in 100 μL phosphate buffer (50 mM, pH  7.0) comprising of 50 μM substrate, 5 μM enzyme.  The  reactions  were  incubated  at  30  °C  for  2  hrs.  The  reactions  were  terminated  with  an  equal  volume  ice-cold  methanol.  HPLC  analysis  of  the  enzyme  reactions  was  carried  out  on  the  Agilent  1260  (Agilent  Technologies  Inc.,  USA)  using  a  reversed-phase  column (Phenomenex Luna, C18, 5 μm, 150 × 4.6  mm) with UV monitoring of the effluent at 304 nm  using the following solvent system (solvent A, 10%  acetonitrile  in  water  supplemented  with  0.1%  formic acid; solvent B, 90% acetonitrile in water);  and  elution  profile  5%  B  to  80  %  B  (0–20min),  100% B (21–24min), 100% B to 5% B (24–25min),  5% B (25–30min); ﬂow rate at 1 mL min−1.

Isolation  of  1a  and  1b.  An  assay  was  scaled  up  and contained 10 µM recombinant Alp1U and 100  µM of substrate 1 in 100mM phosphate buffer (pH  7.0) of total volume 1.5 L at 30 °C for 2  hrs. The  reaction  was  extracted,  each  with  butanone  (3  ×  1.5  L),  and  the  butanone  was  removed  under  vacuum.  The  remaining  residue  was  dissolved  in  methanol  followed  by  semi-preparation  HPLC  using Phenomenex C18 column (250mm × 10mm,  2.5 mL min−1) with an isocratic solvent system (75%  acetonitrile  in  water  supplementing  with  0.05%  formic  acid;  ﬂow  rate  at  2.5  mL  min−1)  to  yield  compounds 1a and 1b.    Mixed  Computational  torsional/low-frequency  mode  conformational  searches  were  done  by  the  Macromodel  10.8.011  software  using  the  Merck  Molecular  Force  Field  (MMFF) with an implicit solvent model for CHCl3  (39). Geometry reoptimizations were carried out at

the  ωB97X/TZVP  (40)  level  with  the  Polarizable  Continuum Model (PCM) for acetonitrile solvent.  Time-dependent  theory  electronic  circular  dichroism  (TDDFT  ECD)  calculations  were  run  with  various  functionals  (B3LYP,  BH&HLYP,  CAM-B3LYP,  PBE0)  and  the  TZVP  basis  set  as  implemented  in  the  Gaussian 09 package with the same or no solvent  model  as in the  preceding  DFT  optimization  step  (41).  ECD  spectra  were  generated  as  sums  of  Gaussians  with  1500-3000  cm-1  widths  at  half-height,  dipole-velocity-computed  rotational strength values (42).  Synthesis  the  diacetate  derivative  of  1a.  The  conversion  of  the  isopropylidene  derivative  was  carried  out  by  following the previously reported  procedure (43).  A  and  pyridinium-p-toluenesulfonate  (0.06  mmol)  were  dissolved  in  2,2-dimethoxy  propane  (2  mL)  and  methanol  (2  mL).  The  solution  was  stirred  overnight  at  room  temperature.  The  reaction  was  stopped  with  aqueous  NaHCO3  (5%,  1  mL)  and  extracted three times with CH2Cl2. The combined  organic  layers  were  reduced  to  dryness  under  residue  was  purified  by  vacuum,  and  semi-preparative  HPLC  to  yield  the  diacetate  derivative  1a  (1a-At,  3.5  mg)  as  a  dark  yellow  powder.  The  structure  of  compound  1a-At  was  confirmed  by  ESIMS  and  NMR  analysis  (Table  S2 and Fig. S3).

Synthesis and X-ray crystallographic analysis of  1b  absolute  pyridonide.  To  conﬁguration  of  1b,  we  reacted  1b  with  p-bromobenzoyl  chloride  to  convert  it  to  its  bromobenzoyl analog, improve  the conditions for  crystallization,  and  introduce  a  heavy  atom.  Following  the  previously  reported  method  (32),  the  and  (0.21  mmol)  and  p-bromobenzoyl  chloride  dimethylaminopyridine  (0.12  mmol)  are  taken  together and slowly dissolved with pyridine (4 mL)  in  a  pear  shaped  Glass  flask.  The  solution  was  stirred at room temperature for 24 hrs. The reaction  was stopped after diluting with water and extracted  with  butanone  (3×5  mL).  The  combined  organic  layers were reduced to dryness under vacuum, and  light  brown  crystals  appear.  A  single  crystal  of  1b-Py  (Fig.  2C  and  Fig.  S5,  Table  S4)  was  diffracted  on  a  XtaLAB  AFC12  (RINC):  Kappa  single diffractometer  with  Cu  Kα  radiation  (λ  =  1.54184  Å).  The  crystal  was  kept  at  104.5(10)  K  during  data  collection.  Using  Olex2,  the  structure  was  solved  with  the  ShelXT  structure  solution  program  using  Intrinsic  Phasing  and  refined  with  the  ShelXL  refinement  package  using  Least  Squares  minimisation.  Crystallographic  data  have  been deposited in the Cambridge Crystallographic  Data  Center  with  the  deposition  number  CCDC  2016594.

Crystallization of Alp1U and  its  mutant  variants  were  performed  using  the  sitting-drop,  vapor-diffusion  method  at  4  °C.  The  purified  protein  was  mixed  with  an  equal  volume  of  reservoir  solution  (0.1  M  MMT  pH  5.0,  25%  PEG1500).  To  obtain  substrate-bound  complex  structure,  and  Alp1UW187F/Y247F  were  soaked  in  crystallization  solution  added  with  2  mM  FST  C  (1)  (10  min,  16  °C),  and  immediately  transferred  to  liquid  nitrogen for cryopreservation.
